                        <summary>
                            
                            <p>On the west wall of the Parāśarēśvra temple.</p>						
                            
                            <p>[Kulōttuṅga III]. Year [3]: 1180-81 A.D.</p>						
                            
                            <p>This inscription begins with the characteristic titles of Yādavarāyas such as <hi rend="italic">Kanuppāra-puravarādhīśvara, Karavāḷa-bhāirava, Veṅkaṭanātha-pādārādhaka</hi>, etc., attributed to Nārasiṅgadēva . . . who was probably a feudatory of Vīrarājēndra who may be identified, on grounds of palaeography, with Kulōttuṅga III.</p>						
                            
                            <p>It records the remission of income from taxes like <hi rend="italic">paṭṭikkāśu</hi> from Muññappūṇḍi a <hi rend="italic">dēvadāna</hi>, by the chief, for two perpetual lamps for the god Tippalādīśvaramuḍaiyamahādēva of Tiruchchugaṉūr in Tiruvēṅgaḍa-kkōṭṭam.</p>						
                            
                        </summary>
                    </msContents>
